s to today, including Marina Abramovic, Sanja Ivekovic, Vlasta Delimar, Tanja Ostojic, Selma Selman and Helena Janecic, along with music legends Lepa Brena and Esma Redžepova. “I am Jugoslovenka” tells a unique story of women’s resistance through the intersection of feminism, socialism and nationalism in East European visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminism and the artszYugoslavia. 0aFeminismzYugoslavia. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aEast European art.  aFeminist performance.  aMarina Abramovic.  aSanja Ivekovic.  aYugoslav feminism.  aYugoslav performance.  aYugoslav socialism.  afeminist art.  agender and socialism.  aperformance art.1 aTumbas, Jasmina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615648840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526156488423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526156488/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles